  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The publication \"Europees burgerschap in de klas,\" released by Leuven University Press in 2022, has not yet recorded any citations or public discourse, indicating an initial period of uptake for this work within the academic community. However, its potential relevance to sustainability and policy is indicated through inferred roles, suggesting that the text may contribute meaningfully to discussions on European citizenship education.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the lack of citation data, \"Europees burgerschap in de klas\" represents a significant addition to the discourse surrounding citizenship education in Europe. The book's publication year, 2022, situates it in a modern context where citizenship is continuously evolving, reflecting societal changes and challenges faced within educational systems. As the work addresses themes of European citizenship, it holds a considerable policy relevance, particularly in relation to one of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), which can be viewed as a measure of its potential impact on the educational landscape.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the inferred role of commercial linkage, highly rated at 0.9, suggests that the book is marketed effectively through major retail platforms like Amazon and Goodreads. This commercial aspect could signify a pathway for increased visibility and accessibility among educators and policymakers engaged in citizenship education. In this regard, the work may gradually carve a niche in academic and public discourse, even if immediate acknowledgment through citations is currently absent.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's emphasis on European citizenship aligns with ongoing dialogues about inclusivity and multiculturalism in education. As the global landscape continues to evolve, resources like this can foster deeper understanding and engagement with citizenship among students. The inferred strength of 0.55 for sustainability and policy relevance underscores the importance of such educational materials in contributing to informed citizenship practices that align with contemporary global challenges.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the current metrics indicate a nascent stage in the book's dissemination, its foundational ideas may eventually stimulate academic and community discourse, helping to shape future educational strategies around citizenship in a European context. Continued engagement and analysis in this arena will be crucial for realizing the themes addressed in \"Europees burgerschap in de klas\" and ensuring that they resonate with the intended audiences in both academic and policy-making circles.</p>",
